@Alex Kontorovich  I hope I understood your analogy. I think you are suggesting we might be better off when, for example, reasoning about a graph, G', with one vertex, v, removed from G. It might be better to do the following?
lemma bar₂ (G) (G') (f : V' → V) (hfinj : Injective f) (hfcard : #V' + 1 = #V) (hfG' : ∀ u v, G'.Adj u v ↔ G.Adj (f u) (f v)) : foo G' := by sorry

I can think of several proofs in Graph theory that uses multiple operations on graphs and if each and every one of them require considering a new function, we would end up having to keep track of several different functions, just to remember where the vertices go, I don't think that is great improvement over, say, G \ {v}.

In fact, do we really lose out on much if we define:
def iteratedDerivedSet (s : Set X) (o : Ordinal) : Set X :=
  if o = 0 then closure s else ⋂ a &lt; o, derivedSet (iteratedDerivedSet s a)

It would let us remove a lot of IsClosed hypotheses, at the very least.

Violeta Hernández 說：

I see your definition of the iterated derived set makes use of limit recursion. As I like to say, you don't need limit recursion like 90% of the time. You can instead do something like this.
def iteratedDerivedSet (s : Set X) (o : Ordinal) : Set X :=
  if o = 0 then s else ⋂ a &lt; o, derivedSet (iteratedDerivedSet s a)



This seems to be an OrdinalApprox.gfpApprox esstentially, at least for closed sets or in a T1 space.
